MrAB1: Person A was given two tickets to the lottery. They won 400.000Đ with one ticket and 200.000Đ with the other ticket.      Person B was given a ticket to one lottery. They won 600.000Đ.        Who is happier?
Game1_1_1: You are going to a sold-out game of your favorite local sports team and you have an extra ticket. The price marked on the ticket is 50.000Đ but this ticket has been offered to you by a friend for free.       You want to get rid of the extra ticket and you know the ticket’s face value price is 50.000Đ. You find someone who wants the ticket. There is no law against charging more than the price marked on the ticket.    What price do you ask for selling the extra ticket if the person you sell it to... ? - Is a friend
Game1_1_2: You are going to a sold-out game of your favorite local sports team and you have an extra ticket. The price marked on the ticket is 50.000Đ but this ticket has been offered to you by a friend for free.       You want to get rid of the extra ticket and you know the ticket’s face value price is 50.000Đ. You find someone who wants the ticket. There is no law against charging more than the price marked on the ticket.    What price do you ask for selling the extra ticket if the person you sell it to... ? - Is a stranger
Game1_2_1: What price would you have asked for if you found out that the ticket’s face value price was 100.000Đ instead? - If they are a friend
Game1_2_2: What price would you have asked for if you found out that the ticket’s face value price was 100.000Đ instead? - If they are a stranger
Drink1: You are on the beach on a hot day, and you would really like a cold drink. A friend offers to go buy the drink from a fancy resort hotel. They ask how much you are willing to pay for the drink: they will only buy it if it costs as much or less than the price you state. You trust your friend, and there is no possibility of bargaining with the bartender.    What price do you tell them?
Gym1 _1: Imagine that you go to the gym on a regular basis. Due to your busy working schedule, you can only go on Monday nights. The membership to the gym allows you to pay 100.000Đ (non-refundable) per session. One Monday, just after you have paid and changed into your gym clothes, you receive a phone call that requires you to leave and forgo your exercise that evening.  How well does each of the following statements capture your feelings about the cost of the missed workout? - I feel like I wasted 100.000Đ
Gym1 _2: Imagine that you go to the gym on a regular basis. Due to your busy working schedule, you can only go on Monday nights. The membership to the gym allows you to pay 100.000Đ (non-refundable) per session. Debriefing: The survey you have completed aims to replicate the mental accounting effect. According to this phenomenon a person attributes different values to the same amount of money based on subjective criteria. Specifically, people tend to subjectively organize economic resources into different mental accounts. In addition, in this study, we measured some individual differences that might have an influence on mental accounting. In particular:   	  	   ●	Scale to measure financial literacy (Lusardi and Mitchell, 2014).  	 	 	  ●	Demographic data (e.g. gender, age or income level)	    Finally, we inform you that we have also used an attentional check to measure respondent engagement. The purpose of this study could not be fully revealed at the beginning of the study to avoid influencing your answers. Now that you have received this information, we ask you to confirm your consent to participate in this study or to withdraw it. In the latter case your data will not be used and will be deleted.
